04662nam a22007935i 9780231519748DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2010    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315197487 a10.7312/mold147622doi  a(DE-B1597)459143  a(OCoLC)676731525  a(OCoLC)979909904  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aNB553.D76bM65 2010eb 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a709.22221 aMolderings, Herbert, eauthor.10aDuchamp and the Aesthetics of Chance :bArt as Experiment /cHerbert Molderings. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource :b37 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Themes in Philosophy, Social Criticism, and the Arts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Idea of the Fabrication -- t2. The 3 Standard Stoppages in the Context of the Large Glass -- t3. The 3 Standard Stoppages as Paintings -- t4. 1936: Duchamp Transforms the Painting Into an Experimental Setup -- t5. Humorous Application of Non-Euclidean Geometry -- t6. The Crisis of the Scientific Concept of Truth -- t7. Pataphysics, Chance, and the Aesthetics of the Possible -- t8. Radical Individualism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMarcel Duchamp is often viewed as an "artist-engineer-scientist," a kind of rationalist who relied heavily on the ideas of the French mathematician and philosopher Henri Poincaré. Yet a complete portrait of Duchamp and his multiple influences draws a different picture. In his 3 Standard Stoppages (1913-1914), a work that uses chance as an artistic medium, we see how far Duchamp subverted scientism in favor of a radical individualistic aesthetic and experimental vision.Unlike the Dadaists, Duchamp did more than dismiss or negate the authority of science. He pushed scientific rationalism to the point where its claims broke down and alternative truths were allowed to emerge. With humor and irony, Duchamp undertook a method of artistic research, reflection, and visual thought that focused less on beauty than on the notion of the "possible." He became a passionate advocate of the power of invention and thinking things that had never been thought before. The 3 Standard Stoppages is the ultimate realization of the play between chance and dimension, visibility and invisibility, high and low art, and art and anti-art. Situating Duchamp firmly within the literature and philosophy of his time, Herbert Molderings recaptures the spirit of a frequently misread artist-and his thrilling aesthetic of chance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aSculpturezFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aBrogden, John.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mold14762423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231519748.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG